        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 5-year-old girl brought in by her parent in the colder season with a short history of upper respiratory symptoms. She looks tired and a little clingy but is alert, breathing comfortably, and able to answer simple questions. Her parent reports nasal congestion and a runny nose, along with a sore throat and cough that began over the last 1-2 days, and she has also complained of a mild headache [MEDLINEPLUS:J00, SNOMED:J00, MEDDIALOG:J00:7].\n\nAt home, {patientName} usually attends kindergarten, plays with toys and coloring books, and spends time with her family. Several children around her have had recent cold-like symptoms, fitting with the fact that common colds spread easily through close personal contact and are especially common in children [MEDLINEPLUS:J00]. She has been drinking a bit less than usual because her throat is sore, but she is still taking small amounts of fluids [SNOMED:J00, MEDLINEPLUS:J00].\n\nOn examination, {patientName} has a stuffy nose, frequent sniffing, and an intermittent dry cough. She says her throat hurts when swallowing. She has a low-grade fever today, but there is no sign of severe distress. The overall picture is of a mild upper respiratory infection affecting the nose and throat [SNOMED:J00, MEDLINEPLUS:J00]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
